Examining the dataset no_additives manually shows that most products in snacks category refer to things such as nuts, dried fruits, etc. Some additives across products have been missed due to ambiguous names (enzyme, natural flavoring, color added). Some products containing hydrogenated oils have not been detected due to ambiguous noting (Hydrogenated oils : soybean, sunflower). For current purposes, this list will remain as it is, matching is good enough. Option is also to manually go through the list and correct wrongly detected items. This is too labour intensive for current purposes due to the unimaginable combination of possible reportings.

I will proceed with assuming that the list of products without additives is representative of the population we’re interested in.

General methodology

(Outlier detection) (Dimension reduction using MCA) Cluster between K = 2…10 (K-modes or K-means) Pick the best clustering configuration based on Average Silhouette Width Assess cluster stability (write a bootstrap algorithm yourself?)

start = Sys.time()
set.seed(42)

sil_scores = numeric(10)
  
for (k in 2:11) {
  clustering_modes = kmodes(data = additives_effects[, 6:47], modes = k, fast = TRUE)
  sil_modes = silhouette(clustering_modes$cluster, dist(additives_effects[, 6:47], method = 'manhattan'))
  sil_scores[k-1] = mean(sil_modes[, 'sil_width'])
}

end = Sys.time()
difference = start - end

Parallel implementation for future purposes

num_cores <- detectCores()   # Use one less than the total number of cores
cl <- makeCluster(num_cores)     # Create a cluster
registerDoParallel(cl)            # Register the cluster for parallel processing

start <- Sys.time()              # Record start time
set.seed(42)                     # Set seed for reproducibility

# Run the silhouette score computations in parallel using foreach
sil_scores <- foreach(k = 1:10, .combine = c) %dopar% {
  clustering_modes <- kmodes(data = additives_effects[, 6:47], modes = k, fast = TRUE)
  sil_modes <- silhouette(clustering_modes$cluster, dist(additives_effects[, 6:47], method = 'manhattan'))
  mean(sil_modes[, 'sil_width'])  # Return mean silhouette width
}

stopCluster(cl)                    # Stop the cluster

end <- Sys.time()                  # Record end time
difference <- end - start          # Calculate time difference
difference
Time difference of -13.35816 mins
for_plot = data.frame(
  k = seq(2, 11),
  sil_score = sil_scores
)

  ylab("Average Silhouette Width") + xlab("k") + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2, 11, by = 1)) + geom_point()

Examine technical effects per cluster

# Create a list to store plots for each cluster
cluster_plots <- list()

# Loop through each unique cluster
for (cluster in unique(additives_effects$clusters_2)) {
  
  # Filter the data for the current cluster
  cluster_data <- additives_effects[additives_effects$clusters_2 == cluster, ]
  
  # Calculate column sums for technical effect columns
  additives_rank <- colSums(cluster_data[, 6:47] == 1)
  
  # Convert to data frame and arrange to get the top 25 effects
  additives_rank_df <- stack(additives_rank) %>%
    arrange(desc(values)) %>%
    head(25)
  
  # Rename columns for clarity
  names(additives_rank_df) <- c("value", "name")
  
  # Create the plot for the current cluster
  p <- ggplot(data = additives_rank_df, aes(x = value, y = reorder(name, value))) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', fill = 'steelblue2') +
    xlab('Count') +
    ylab(NULL) +
    theme_minimal() +
    ggtitle(paste("Top 25 Technical Effects for Cluster", cluster))
  
  # Store the plot in the list
  cluster_plots[[as.character(cluster)]] <- p
}

# To display a plot, you can use print(cluster_plots[[<cluster_number>]]) for specific clusters,
# or display all at once
cluster_plots

Most interesting result from this clustering exercise is the finding that without using the column ‘is_upf_marker’, clusters that pertain to this indicator can nevertheless be identified. Seems to come down to the observation that highly processed foods use more additives and especially those that indicate ultra-processing.

Let’s try to explore the stability of the cluster configurations.

kmodesCBI = function(data = data, k = 3) {
  clustering = kmodes(data = data, modes = k, fast = TRUE)
  
  data$cluster = clustering$cluster
  cluster_membership_list <- lapply(unique(data$cluster), function(cl) {
    data$cluster == cl
    })
  names(cluster_membership_list) <- as.character(unique(data$cluster))
  
  out = list(
    result = clustering$cluster,
    nc = k,
    clusterlist = cluster_membership_list,
    partition = clustering$cluster,
    clustermethod = 'kmodes'
  )
}
stability_eval = clusterboot(data = additives_effects[, 6:47], B = 5, bootmethod = 'boot',
